msg:
Add 2 sample projects for GoogleMobileVision pod.

BarcodeDetector: This demo demonstrates basic barcode detection and
integration with AVFoundation. The app highlights barcodes in the
camerapreview frame.

MultiDetector: This demo demonstrates how to use the MultiDataOutput in
GoogleMVDataOutput pod to integrate both face and barcode detectors with
the video pipeline. The app draws overlay on top of detected barcodes
and faces.

msg:
samples/assistant/embedded-python-sdk: expose converse responses

Instead of returning a generator of audio samples, return a generator
of ConverseResponse proto messages and exposes a series of generator
helpers.

converse(input_samples[]) -> ConverseResponses[]
wait_end_of_utterance(ConverseResponse[]) -> None
iter_assistant_audio(ConverseResponse[]) -> output_samples[]

The goal is to allow the caller to:
- access the underlying proto if needed (transcription-text, ifttt_response).
- expose a way to explicitly wait for end of utterance
- expose a way to easily iterate on output sample data

Let me know what you think!

msg:
samples/assistant/embedded-sdk-python: kill EmbeddedAssistant wrapper

This remove the EmbeddedAssistant wrapper and replace it with
assistant_helpers: a module with helpers functions.

This has the following advantages:
- move locking to PyAudio stream where it belong
- less encapulsation, surface the actual gRPC API call and make it
  easier to correlate with generated API reference.
- give back control to __main__ over recording and playback (asked by
  EAP testers)
- net LOCs loss :)

Also add logging for ConverseRequest.

msg:
google-assistant-sdk: add device registration sample

Usage:
googlesamples-assistant-devicetool register --model 'my-model' --type LIGHT --trait Blink ... --device 'my-device'
googlesamples-assistant-devicetool register-model --model 'my-model' --type LIGHT --trait Blink ...
googlesamples-assistant-devicetool register-device --device 'my-device' --model 'my-model' ...
googlesamples-assistant-devicetool get --model my-model
googlesamples-assistant-devicetool get --device my-device
googlesamples-assistant-devicetool list --model
googlesamples-assistant-devicetool list --device

Note:
This reuses google-oauthlib-tool credentials.
If the device model already exists it will update it.
If the device instance already exists it will delete and re-create it.

"""
In general, calls to ReadStream and WriteStream on different
streams in different threads are probably safe. That means that if you
are doing Blocking I/O, one thread may read and write to one stream,
and another thread may read and write to another.
"""

Add a new way to pass data into the app via adb.

Originally there was only a set of extras that could be specified on the
command line to set the package name, media browser component, and pass
in a URI, search, or media ID.

I've updated it to allow passing in the package name and a query
that the developer may want to execute, and I've done it via a 'deep
link' type of structure. I hope this will make it relatively easy for
developers to use, and won't require using very short names for extras,
which is typically not recommended best practice.

If developers require the ability to pass in complex URIs (with
multiple parameters) then they can fall back to an updated set of extras
that follow recommended best practices in their naming.

Configure steps should populate origState/Metadata

This is necessary for chained tests (e.g. if from STATE_STOPPED, a
Play-Pause test is run, the Play half of the test would mark
STATE_STOPPED as valid since STATE_STOPPED is the original state for
that half of the test, but the Pause half should not consider
STATE_STOPPED to be valid since the Pause half starts in STATE_PLAYING).

msg:
Don't tint icons of app-provided media items

Tinting only makes sense for icons which are known to be
monochrome/transparent. The app-provided media icons, however, will also
show colored album art and logo bitmaps which turn into black filled
squares when tinted.

Format and render `android.media.extra` metadata

According to [Android Auto's docs](https://developer.android.com/training/cars/media#metadata-indicators) for metadata indicators, there are a few more extras that should be exposed for a complete UI rendering that `android-media-controller` doesn't take in account.

I'm updating the code to consider `DOWNLOAD_STATUS`, `BT_FOLDER_TYPE` and `METADATA_KEY_ADVERTISEMENT`, and render them as `Long` values in the "test" screen. See screenshots.

The lint error reports if your simply using an older version of a library.
We don't want users builds to stop simply because a newer version of a
library is available, but this is useful during our continuous builds or
development builds, so it's now a project property.

You can build the native plugin alone with: ../gradlew -PlintAbortOnError build
Or the whole project with: ./build_all
which will enable lintAbort automatically.
